[[File:HouMuWuDingFullView.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Houmuwu ding at [[National Museum of China]]]] The '''Houmuwu ding''' ({{zh|s=后母戊鼎|p=Hòumǔwù dǐng}}), formerly called '''Simuwu ding''' ({{zh|s=司母戊鼎|p=Sīmǔwù dǐng}}), is a rectangular bronze ''[[ding (vessel)|ding]]'' (sacrificial vessel, one of the common types of [[Chinese ritual bronze]]s) of the ancient Chinese [[Shang dynasty]]. It is the largest piece of bronzeware to survive from anywhere in the ancient world.<ref name="nmc">{{cite web|url=http://www.chinaculture.org/gb/en_museum/2003-09/24/content_29769.htm|title=The National Museum of China|publisher=China Culture|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527232757/http://www.chinaculture.org/gb/en_museum/2003-09/24/content_29769.htm|archivedate=2014-05-27|df=}}</ref> It was unearthed in Wuguan Village, [[Anyang]], [[Henan]] in 1939.
==Owner== The ''ding'' is named for the inscription in [[Chinese bronze inscriptions|bronze ware script]] on the interior wall, which reads "Queen Mother Wu" ({{zh|c=后母戊|p=Hòumǔwù}}).<ref name="Song. 2011">Li Song. ''Chinese Bronze Ware'' (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2011, {{ISBN|978-0-521-18685-8}}), p. 28.</ref> This is the [[temple name]] of [[Fu Jing]], a queen of [[Wu Ding]].{{sfnp|Zeng|1993|p=71}} The ''ding'' was made after her death, presumably by her son, [[Zu Geng of Shang]].{{sfnp|Li|2012|p=13}} Whilst the ding itself was unearthed in 1939, [[Fu Jing]]'s tomb<ref>[[Yinxu]], tomb 260</ref> was not located until 1959, and was found to have been [[Grave robbery|robbed out]].{{sfnp|Li|2012|p=13}}
==Description== [[File:Chiang and HouMuWu Ding.jpg|thumb|[[Chiang Kai-shek]] (right) inspecting the Houmuwu ding in 1948]] The ''ding'' is of the rectangular type, with four legs. It is 133 centimetres high, 110 centimetres wide, 79 centimetres deep, and weighs 832.84 kilograms.<ref name="Song. 2011"/> Compared to earlier ''ding'', such as the [[Duling rectangular ding]], it is wider and its walls are thicker, making it much more massive.<ref name=LiSong>Li Song. ''Chinese Bronze Ware'', p. 30.</ref> Each side has a blank space in the middle, surrounded by a band of decoration featuring ''[[taotie]]'' (animal faced creatures) and ''[[Kui (Chinese mythology)|kuilong]]'' (one-legged dragons).<ref name=LiSong /> There are two handles, each decorated on the exterior with two [[tiger]]s facing each other, their jaws closing around a human head in between them, an image which is also found on [[Fu Hao]] battle axes.<ref name=LiSong />
==Inscription debate== The inscription was originally read as ''sīmǔwù'' (司母戊), but since the 1970s scholars have reached the consensus that the first character should be read as ''hou'' (后), meaning queen, which is the mirror-image of ''si'' (司) in [[oracle bone script]]. The [[National Museum of China]] has officially corrected its name.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://english.cntv.cn/20110328/102842.shtml |title="Houmuwu Quadripod" debuts at National Museum of China |newspaper=CCTV |date=28 March 2011 |accessdate=20 January 2014 }}</ref> This reading of the inscription meant that the owner of the ding was supposed to have been a wife of [[Wu Yi of Shang]] (reigned c. 1147–1112 BC),<ref>[http://www.indiana.edu/~g380/3.4-Kings-2010.pdf Shang Kingship and Shang Kinship]</ref><ref name="ReferenceA">[[The Cambridge History of Ancient China]]</ref> and the dedicator her son, [[Wen Ding]]<ref name="Song. 2011"/> (reigned c. 1112–1102 BC).<ref name="ReferenceA"/><ref>[http://ancienthistory.about.com/od/chinadynasties/p/032509ShangDynst.htm ''Shang Dynasty'' by N.S. Gill], About.com Guide</ref> However, understanding the first character as ''hou'' makes it the [[temple name]] of [[Fu Jing]], who lived earlier.{{sfnp|Zeng|1993|p=71}}
